author: Sara Heilman
servings: 2
---

In a #small pot{}, combine @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1}, half the @Southwest Spice Blend{1/2%tablespoon}, @Turmeric{1/4%tsp} (1/2 tsp for 4 servings), and @water{3/4%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4). (Be sure to measure the turmeric—we sent more!)

Bring to a boil, then stir in @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, wash and dry produce.

Halve, core, and thinly slice @Long Green Pepper{1} into strips. Dice @Tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}. Zest and quarter @Lime{1}.

Heat a large drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper; cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @Shrimp{10%ounce} dry with paper towels; season with remaining Southwest Spice Blend.

> Rinse shrimp under cold water, then pat dry with paper towels. Swap in shrimp for chicken; cook, stirring occasionally, until opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Cook through the rest of the step as instructed.

Once green pepper is slightly softened, add shrimp and a large drizzle of oil to pan. Cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp is cooked through and green pepper is caramelized, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add @Tex-Mex Paste{1%tablespoon} and @water{1/4%cup}; cook, stirring, until sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Turn off heat.

While shrimp cooks, in a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a squeeze of lime juice, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @Sour Cream{3%tablespoon}, lime zest, a squeeze of lime juice, salt, and pepper.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice between bowls and top with shrimp and peppers, salsa fresca, and lime sour cream. Drizzle with @Hot Sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste. Serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.